Join us on May 27 for the official opening ceremony of Rescue Jr.! Enjoy a speech from Park President Jim Lake, an exciting live musical performance, ribbon cannons, and a ceremonial ribbon cutting!​

​After the ceremony, have tons of family-friendly fun exploring the Mini Rescue Training Zone play area, climbing to the top of the newly refurbished Rescue Boat in the center of the Rescue Bay Splash Zone, meeting animal conservation ambassadors and members of the SeaWorld Rescue team, getting a close-up look at real rescue vehicles, and so much more!​

The ceremony will begin at 10:15am, Rescue Jr. will open to the public immediately after.

We're starting off the fly fishing season over at Dragonfly Pond within Meadowlands (by the last bridge)! Come learn how to fish and see what you might find with our instructors from 10am-4:15pm. Fishing equipment is free and included with a Day Pass or Passholder membership. Please note that a fishing license is required, per the California Department of Fish and Wildlife. If you already have one, bring it during your next visit or you can purchase a one-day fishing license in the Exit Shop. Catch and release only.

And stay tuned for updates on when Ladybug Pond will be open for fly fishing!

The birds are back! Recently, guests have enjoyed the return of the macaws and eclectus parrots to their habitats throughout the zoo 🦜 Now, after a thorough risk assessment by Happy Hollow's animal care team, the aviary birds and turkey vultures are back in their habitats as well! Come by and see which ones you can spot 🐦 

Please note: at this time, for the continued safety of Happy Hollow's birds, guests will be able to view the aviary birds from outside but not walk through the aviary. We will continue to monitor the presence of Highly Pathogenic Avian Influenza, and will keep our guests updated as the risk status changes.

Before Ridgway was the healthy dolphin he is today, he had some health issues to overcome - and we don’t just mean the damage to his dorsal fin and flukes. At intake, the care team took this x-ray and were able to diagnose him with bilateral pneumonia. With the infection identified, they successfully nursed him back to health.

Join us in the World's Largest Swimming Lesson on June 22!🥽🌊

Swimming is a life-saving skill and is a vital tool in drowning prevention. We’re teaming up with the World Waterpark Association to build awareness about the fundamental importance of teaching others to swim. The aquatics team at South Bay Shores Waterpark will join other aquatics facilities across the country to conduct the World’s Largest Swimming Lesson!

For more details and to register, visit: https://www.cagreatamerica.com/events/worlds-largest-swimming-lesson

This Thursday, May 25, is the 2023 Senior Safari Kickoff! Preceding this first event of the Senior Safari season, there will be a special celebration starting at 8:30 a.m. honoring May as Older Americans Month. Speakers will include County Supervisor Chavez, San José City Councilmembers Doan and Foley, and San José Parks, Recreations and Neighborhood Services Director Jon Cicirelli. Bay Area radio personality and retired Happy Hollow Foundation Board Member Lissa Kreisler will emcee the festivities. 

Senior Safari, presented by Kaiser Permanente, allows adults 50+ to take over Happy Hollow with free admission and parking between 9 and 10 a.m. Senior Safari is a joint program of Happy Hollow Foundation and Happy Hollow Park & Zoo.

Happy World Turtle Day! 🐢🎉 Honu (Green Sea Turtles) are not only fascinating but also play a vital role in our ecosystem. Take a moment to learn more about them and find ways to protect them and their habitats during your next visit!

Happy World Turtle Day! #DYK that all tortoises are turtles, but not all turtles are tortoises? Turtles are any animal in order Testudines or Chelonia, while tortoises are a special subset of these shelled creatures. Unique from turtles as a whole, tortoises have stumpy, elephant-like feet; tall, domed shells; and are terrestrial and herbivorous. Happy Hollow has several of each, and we are always eager to celebrate them!

📸: Keeper Tarynn and Krystel M.

Today is a historic day, not only for our brand, but for conservation as a whole. With the opening of SeaWorld Abu Dhabi, our dedication to animal care, rescue, and conservation expands to a whole new part of the world. Today is a historic day, not only for our brand, but for conservation as a whole. Tree Kangaroos are endemic to Papua New Guinea and part of the AZA SAFE (Saving Animals from Extinction) program. Their diet consists mostly of fruits, seeds, and nuts, making them primary seed dispersers that contribute to creating and maintaining healthy forests. These species are threatened by loss of habitat, so you can help protect them by looking for Forest Stewardship Council certification when you purchase wood and wood products.

Opening day is here! Here are some updates for this season:
*We will be open 5 days a week this season - we are CLOSED on Tuesday and Wednesday - our hours are 10am-5pm on days we are open weather permitting
*In the Summer & Fall it is free to enter the park to shop and dine and ride wristbands are available for purchase at our front gate for $32 per person age 3 and up. Anyone who is riding the rides does need a wristband.
*No reservations required over the Summer & Fall season
*One of our favorite rides- The Paratrooper- is in the final stages of refurbishment and will be opening later this summer, we can't wait to debut this ride for you all because it will be beautiful! Our granny bug ride is also currently closed for refurbishment and we will update you all on the progress as it comes along! 

For more details including our full calendar, more detailed pricing information and a list of rides and safety requirements please visit our website northpolecolorado.com

We can't wait to see you this year!

Today is Endangered Species Day, so we wanted to share the story of Georgia, a rescued green sea turtle! ​

Georgia was rescued in October 2022 after a family visiting from Georgia spotted her floating from their boat (hence how she got her name). They watched her for several hours before SeaWorld was called to help, and with assistance from the Coast Guard, we transported her back to our rescue center where she was stabilized. It was discovered that she is missing her left front flipper, but no other injuries were found. She responded well to treatment and can now swim and dive normally despite her missing flipper. She will soon be returned to San Diego Bay where there is a resident population of green sea turtles.​

This turtle species is considered endangered, mainly due to entanglement in fishing equipment, beach development, and habit degradation. Let Georgia's story remind you to always recycle, as it is crucial to helping these and other turtle species thrive in their natural environments!

This Endangered Species Day, it’s important to remember that accredited zoos and aquariums play an important role in rescuing and preserving many threatened or endangered species. Take Tyonek, for example. He is a rescued Cook Inlet beluga whale, which is a population of belugas in Alaska that are considered endangered. Since being deemed non-releasable and joining the pod at SeaWorld San Antonio, Tyonek has been a part of a number of studies that have helped us learn more about the biology of the species so we can better support the conservation of wild populations.

In honor of #EndangeredSpeciesDay, let's learn about Sawfish 🌎 Smalltooth sawfish are critically endangered and these incredible animals get their names because of their rostrums, or “saws” – long, flat snouts edged with pairs of teeth which are used to locate, stun and kill prey. They have 25-29 teeth on each side of their rostrum! Learn more about sawfish during your next visit to Shark Encounter!

Did you know the Giant Dipper was built in just 47 days? To bring the iconic roller coaster to life, the 50-person crew used 327,000 board feet of lumber, 743,000 galvanized nails, 63,000 pounds of steel track & safety iron, 2,740 gallons of paint, 3,150 light bulbs plus lots of other material. The Giant Dipper was declared a National Historic Landmark in 1987, is the fourth oldest coaster in the country (continuously operating in its original location), and is the ninth oldest coaster in the world! #TBT

#DidYouKnow that Two-Toed Sloths are some of the slowest animals on the planet? 🐻⏰ In fact, they move so slowly that algae grows on their fur, creating the perfect camouflage in the trees! 🌳🍃

But don't let their laid-back lifestyle fool you - Two-Toed Sloths are incredibly strong and can hold onto branches with their powerful claws for hours on end 💪 They even sleep upside down and can turn their heads a full 270 degrees to keep an eye out for predators! 😲👀

Come visit Oscar and Maya and witness these amazing creatures in action. Just don't be surprised if you feel the urge to slow down and take it easy after spending time with them! 😴🌴 #TwoToedSloths #WildAdventures

Captive reared monarch butterflies are not as strong as their wild counterparts, which means they are less likely to be able to complete their migration and are more susceptible to Ophryocystis elektroscirrha, a protozoan parasite that infects monarchs. When captive monarchs are released, they breed with wild monarchs, making the entire population weaker. Enjoy monarchs in the wild instead- look for caterpillars on leaves and adults sipping nectar from flowers! #PlayitSAFE #SAFEMonarchs #FeedTheMigration #SavingSpecies #SAFEMonarchNetwork #MonarchConservation #MonarchButterfly #MoreThanMonarchs

It's National Chocolate Chip Day⁠! Our cookies are Mrs. Claus' own recipe, and as far as Santa's concerned, they are the BEST chocolate cookies around. ⁠
⁠
Want to make Santa's Favorite Cookies at home? Here's the recipe straight from The Gingerbread Bakery:⁠
⁠
1/2 cup melted butter⁠
1/3 cup granulated sugar⁠
1/2 cup packed light brown sugar⁠
1 large egg⁠
1 teaspoon of good vanilla extract⁠
1/2 teaspoon of baking soda⁠
1/2 teaspoon of salt⁠
1 1/2 cups all purpose flour⁠
1 1/2 cups chocolate chips⁠
⁠
This dough needs to be chilled!⁠
⁠
1. Melt butter and place into large mixing bowl. Then add granulated sugar and brown sugar and mix on a low speed until smooth. Mix in egg and vanilla extract, then make sure you mix on medium speed until everything is well mixed.⁠
2. Next, mix in baking soda and salt. Now, slowly mix in the flour...mix just until the batter is smooth. Now the best part, slowly mix in the chocolate chips.⁠
3. Now, line a cookie sheet with parchment paper. Scoop out 2 tablespoons balls of dough. Cover with plastic wrap and chill for at least 2 hours.⁠
4. After 2 hours, preheat your oven to 350 degrees. Line a second cookie sheet with parchment paper.⁠
5. Remove the chilled dough from the refrigerator and place them 2 inches apart on the cookie sheet. Bake for 11-15 mins. Make sure the edges are light golden and the tops are no longer shiney. Let the cookies cool on the sheet for at least 10 mins before removing.⁠
⁠
Enjoy!

This neonate male dolphin was rescued Wednesday, May 10 after being spotted alone and in distress near Anclote Key. He was transported to our rescue center in Orlando because of our extensive experience caring for young dolphins. Upon arrival, our veterinary team performed an exam and determined that he was hours to days old, making his rescue all the more critical for survival. We are happy to report he is swimming on his own and learning to take a bottle, but he is still considered to be in critical condition. This baby (and others like him) would not have a chance if not for the incredible rescue work and partnership of accredited zoological facilities and the Southeast Stranding Network who come together to do what is best for animals every day. We thank Epic Tails Charters who originally spotted him, Clearwater Marine Aquarium and Pasco Sheriff's Office for transporting him to us for rehabilitation, and NOAA Fisheries Service for their leadership.

May 14 is World Migratory Bird Day! AZA's SAFE (Saving Animals from Extinction) program includes the over 300 species of songbirds that spend part of their annual cycle in North America. Songbird populations are in decline in North America due to habitat loss, climate change, building collisions and predation from outdoor domestic cats. Learn about ways you can help North American Songbirds: https://nationalzoo.si.edu/migratory-birds/7-simple-actions-live-bird-friendlyr

Talk about a holiday you can really sink your teeth into! Come celebrate National Apple Pie Day with us today at Billy's BBQ! Grab a slice for $4 while supplies last.⁠
⁠
Apple pie has been around since the Middle Ages! A Dutch cookbook dated 1514 lists a recipe for Appeltaerten. It called for a standard pie crust, slices of soft seedless apples, and a few tasty spices—specifically cardamom, ginger, cinnamon, nutmeg, clove, mace, and sugar—all cooked up in a traditional Dutch oven. The English also had their version of apple pie, which dates back to the time of Chaucer. ⁠
In Sweden, apple crumble was the gold-standard. Traditional Swedish apple crumble requires breadcrumbs or rolled oats instead of pastry, and is served up with custard or ice cream. ⁠
In France, apple pie is served upside-down as a tarte tatin.⁠
⁠
Does your family have a special Apple Pie recipe?

ICYMI: We are excited to announce a new program we developed at Silverwood called Fostering Family Fun. Starting in May 2023, Silverwood will offer foster children in the state of Idaho the opportunity to visit Silverwood for FREE once a year through our new Fostering Family Fun program! Family members will also qualify for discounted tickets when showing a valid Idaho ID at the gate. This program is designed to help foster families make new memories and have fun together.

In 2023, we are only offering this program to the state of Idaho, but we are looking at ways to expand to our neighboring states in the coming years.

If you know anyone that could benefit from this program, they can find more information at https://sw4.fun/Foster

A few weeks ago, our SeaWorld Orlando Rescue team helped with the rescue and onsite return of Fergie, a male dolphin calf who was observed swimming with mother Skipper with fishing line cutting deeply into his tail flukes. Alongside partners Brookfield Zoo, MyFWC Florida Fish and Wildlife, Clearwater Marine Aquarium, Mote Marine Laboratory & Aquarium, University of Florida College of Veterinary Medicine, FAU Harbor Branch Oceanographic Institute, Friends of Rookery Bay, and Collier County Sheriff's Office, the team was able to assess both dolphins, remove the gear from Fergie and clean his wounds before releasing them together.

SkyPark at Santa's Village is pleased to introduce TODDLER TIME!⁠
⁠
Starting May 11th, bring your little ones (ages 5 and under) to the park on Thursday mornings starting at 10:30am (meet at Kringles!) for fun activities, crafts, and sensory experiences designed just for them! 🌳🎨👶

This special event is included with a SkyPark Day Pass or Monthly/Annual Pass. Plus, children aged 3 and under get in for free! Don't miss out on this exciting park enhancement Thursdays for you and your little ones to have a blast at the park.⁠

Join us for special events each week created with them in mind, like the wigglefest dance party, the floor maze, sensory discovery workshop, the mini olympics, rock painting, music exploration, and more!⁠
⁠
Doors open for Toddler Time at 9:00am so that parents have the option to purchase coffee or breakfast at Kringle’s Coffee & Gifts before the fun starts. Please note that parents must remain with their children and supervise them at all times. Toddler Time activities are guided and parental participation is encouraged.⁠
⁠
Paid admission is required for entry to SkyPark at Santa’s Village. Annual Passholders and Monthly Members get in for free. All guests entering the park must complete a waiver, regardless of participation in activities.⁠
⁠
More info here: https://skyparksantasvillage.com/toddler-time-2023/

The key to a perfect Moscow mule is quality ginger beer, which is why we use 'Cock'n Bull' Ginger Beer! ⁠
⁠
Fun Fact: In the 1940’s ginger beer imports were hard to find here in America and so Cock’n Bull Ginger Beer was born. It was developed by a man named Jack Morgan, owner of the famous Cock’n Bull Restaurant in Hollywood. ⁠
Jack Morgan and John G. Martin of Heublein, a major spirits distributor, sat down for a drink. Jack Morgan wanted to introduce America to Cock’n Bull Ginger Beer and John Martin had the uphill challenge of marketing his newly acquired vodka brand to Americans who preferred whiskey and gin. To boost sales of their individual products, the men created the classic drink we now refer to as the Moscow Mule. An authentic Moscow Mule is made with Cock’n Bull Ginger Beer, vodka and lime and served over ice. So, next time you're at the Pedal Pub, try an authentic Moscow Mule! ⁠
⁠
source: http://cocknbull.us/history/⁠
@officialcocknbull

The parrots are back! 🦜 Due to the avian influenza outbreak, Happy Hollow's birds have been kept inside for quite some time to protect them from the virus, which is fatal to many birds and often transmitted through the feces of wild waterfowl. It is now becoming clear that the virus will not be disappearing anytime soon, so the Happy Hollow zoo team went through a thorough risk assessment process to determine if the birds should be given outdoor access again. The macaws and eclectus parrots are the first birds to be moved back outside on a trial basis. If all goes well, we will have an update on the aviary birds coming next. Keep an eye out during your next Happy Hollow visit and you should be able to see these beautiful parrot species in their habitats, and definitely hear them. 😜

📸 Keeper Mary and Krystel M.

'Twas the night before Opening Day,
And all through the park, not a sound did sway,
The coasters stood tall, awaiting the thrills,
While visitors dreamed of loops and hills.

The staff had worked hard, to prepare for this night,
Cleaning and fixing, to make everything right,
Thunder Canyon sparkled, gleaming and bright,
Ready for splashes and screams of delight.

The rides were inspected, the safety checks done,
Everything was in place, the fun had begun,
The food venues stocked up, with treats for all,
The gift shops overflowing, with toys and dolls.

And as the night grew darker, the excitement did grow,
For soon the park would open, and the crowds would flow,
With butterflies in their stomachs, and smiles on their faces,
The visitors would come, to enjoy all the places.

So let's raise a cheer, for Silverwood on this night,
For the park is ready, the rides a delight,
With opening day soon, go grab all your friends,
To Silverwood Theme Park, where the fun never ends.

This 1893 photo shows an adventurous swimmer far from shore, which was unusual for the time. On the shoreline (left to right), there's the Neptune Bath House, which offered water shows and popular Saturday night mussel bakes, and the Miller-Leibbrandt Plunge that had hundreds of dressing rooms, a glass-enclosed observatory, café, billiard parlor, card room, plus a heated pool featuring springboards all around the perimeter and a flying trapeze. #TBT

To celebrate Arbor Day, SeaWorld San Diego planted 100 trees around our parking lot. Trees are an essential part of every ecosystem – they help clean the air we breathe, prevent soil erosion and rainwater runoff, and provide shelter and protection for many birds and mammals. We're excited to help contribute to the @CityofSanDiego's Climate Action Plan goal of increasing our urban tree canopy cover. We encourage everyone to look after your local trees and ecosystems – today and every day! #arborday

Today, we celebrate Marine Mammal Rescue Day. In 2020, Kupa'a and Li'i were brought to our park in need of lifelong sanctuary. 

The two California sea lions were initially rescued a few months apart by the @pacificmmc, and released back into the wild following care and rehabilitation. Not long after, they needed to be rescued again. NOAA deemed them unfit to be re-released back into the wild, and they have since called our park home.

Here, they receive 24/7 care from our Animal Care Specialists, where they receive the love and attention they need. Kupa'a and Li'i spend their days educating the public about their kind, inspiring guests to do their part in preserving our waters so that their species can thrive in the wild.

Well WADDLE you know, it's World Penguin Day! 🐧Here are some fun facts about the penguins who call Penguin Encounter home:​

🧊 Adélies build their nests with stones and are known to steal stones from the nests of rival breeding pairs.​
🧊 Chinstrap penguins may be the most abundant penguin, with a population estimated at 7.5 million breeding pairs.​
🧊 Emperor penguins are known to toboggan, sliding across ice on their bellies.​
🧊 When constricted, the pupils of a king penguin's eye are square.​
🧊The early English explorers named the Macaroni Penguin. They thought the yellow feathers of this penguin were like a fancy young man called a 'macaroni.'​
🧊The discovery of South America's Magellanic penguin was chronicled during the journey of Spanish explorer Ferdinand Magellan in 1520.

VEM CONHECER 5 CURIOSIDADES SOBRE A DRAGON! 🐲

A Montanha-Russa do Playland - presente nas unidades #Osasco e #Salvador, oferece muita alegria e doses moderadas de adrenalina.

Vem com a gente conhecer 5 curiosidades sobre essa atração tão querida:

1. DE ONDE VEIO: a Dragon faz o maior sucesso por aqui, mas ela não é brasileira! Ela foi fabricada na Italia (por um dos melhores fabricantes do mundo, a Zamperla) e chegou ao Brasil de navio. 🚢

2.  IRMÃS: A Dragon é tão legal que diversas 'irmãs' dela estão espalhadas por parques do mundo todo! No Brasil existem ao menos 05 versões que divertem e encantam a galera! E 03 delas pertencem ao Play! Além das que estão no Playland, existe uma lá no Playcenter Family (@playcenterfamilyoficial) 🐉🐲🐉

3. MUITA GENTE: A cada ciclo a Dragon pode divertir até 24 pessoas, por dia mais de 1.500 pessoas passam pelos trilhos da atração. 🎢

4.  VELOCIDADE: A velocidade que o carrinho da Dragon atinge é sempre a mesma, mas a sensação de velocidade pode aumentar se você escolher senta-se nos últimos assentos. Experimente! 😆

5. TUDO SEGURO: Para brincar com total segurança é preciso obedecer a altura mínima e outras restrições de segurança. Na frente da atração você encontra todas essas informações. 🤓

Gostou de saber essas curiosidades? Que tal chamar os amigos, toda a família e curtir um passeio emocionante na nossa montanha-russa? Estamos esperando por você!

Want to take an earth-tastic tour? Take a Northwoods Express Train Ride, this electric-powered train takes you on a tour through our beautiful Meadowlands. Discover a whole new world of flora and fauna as the train meanders through this unique alpine ecosystem, or hop off midway through to explore the Northwoods Hiking Trail (when open). ⁠
⁠
The key to conservation is education! Together, we can ensure a greener, healthier, and more resilient future for all. 🌳🌲

It is with heavy hearts that we share “Freeway,” the rescued sea lion, passed away yesterday -- surrounded with love from his devoted care and rescue teams. His adventurous spirit won the hearts of all San Diegans and he will be remembered for that and so much more. Before Freeway was rescued last year, he had contracted a progressive disease that our animal care experts diagnosed. Despite extensive treatment, the disease caused his health to deteriorate over time. Given his decline, the team made the extremely difficult, but compassionate decision to humanely euthanize him. We are grateful for the support of the community and all of Freeway’s fans who, like us, loved him so very much. We will miss him dearly.

#DidYouKnow Ring-Tailed Lemurs are the most recognizable lemur species due to their black and white striped tails? 🦝🖤 Here are some fun facts about these adorable primates:

• Ring-tailed lemurs are native to Madagascar and are the only primate species that live exclusively on the island.

• They are social animals and live in groups called troops.

• They are herbivores and have a diet that includes fruit, leaves, and flowers.

Have you seen our Ring-Tailed Lemurs during your visit to Wild Adventures? Share your favorite lemur memory in the comments below! 🦝💬

📸: Kristen, Zoo Keeper

The safety of our guests and associates has always been our top priority at California's Great America. Over the past two years, there have been increasing incidents of unruly and inappropriate behavior across our industry and at other major entertainment venues. We are committed to keeping California's Great America a place where families and friends come together to enjoy a one-of-a-kind park, full of fun experiences and immersive entertainment.

As part of that commitment, we are implementing a chaperone policy beginning Saturday, April 22, 2023.

Under this policy, all guests ages 15 years old or younger must be accompanied by a chaperone who is at least 21 years old in order to be admitted to, or remain in, the park after 4:00 p.m. local time to close.  The chaperone must present a valid government-issued photo identification with date of birth at ticket entry. One (1) chaperone may accompany no more than ten (10) guests ages 15 or younger per day. In addition, the chaperone must accompany their party during entry, remain inside the park during their visit, and be available by phone throughout their stay. Guests ages 15 years old or younger who are found inside the park unaccompanied by a chaperone will be subject to ejection. This chaperone requirement applies to all California's Great America ticket and season passholders.

We believe these changes will help ensure that California's Great America continues to have a positive atmosphere where generations of families and friends can gather for a day of safe fun and good food. Millions of guests have counted on us for exactly that, and we will continue to deliver on that promise for generations to come.

For more information, visit https://www.cagreatamerica.com/code-of-conduct

Have you ever seen the Happy Hollow capybaras swimming? #DYK, in the wild, capybaras will pee and poop in rivers to help carry their waste downstream? That way, the capybaras' predators, like jaguars, have a harder time tracking the capybaras' location 🧠 #brainpower So the next time you see the capybaras swimming, it's very possible that they are using their natural toilet 💩🚽

📸 Keeper Michelle

We're here to brighten your Tuesday with a cute animal spotlight - Meet Chickaree! ​

Chickaree was rescued on June 26, 2021, by the Marine Mammal Center at Big River Beach in Mendocino County. Due to her young age and vision impairments, she was deemed non-releasable and relocated to SeaWorld San Diego (the only facility in North America to have a permit to house this special species) to join sea lions, harbor seals and Guadalupe fur seal friends. ​

😊 Você sabia que o Playland é uma empresa do Grupo Playcenter?

🎠 O Playland foi criado em 1981 pelo Grupo Playcenter, empresa que durante os anos de 1973 e 2012 operou com muito sucesso o Parque de Diversões mais amado do Brasil.

😍 Com a missão de levar a alegria e a diversão dos Parques para dentro dos Shoppings, hoje o Playland está presente nos principais endereços de São Paulo e da Bahia, atendendo milhares de famílias que buscam por momentos de lazer e emoção.

😊 Confira nossas unidades:

Estado de São Paulo:

- Playland Center Norte (Shopping Center Norte - São Paulo)
- Playland Eldorado (Shopping Eldorado - São Paulo)
- Playland Interlagos (Shopping Interlagos - São Paulo)
- Playland Metrô Tatuapé (Shopping Metrô Tatuapé - São Paulo)
- Playland Osasco (Shopping União de Osasco - Osasco)
- Playland Grand Plaza (Grand Plaza Shopping - Santo André)

Estado da Bahia:

- Playland Salvador (Shopping da Bahia - Salvador)

E também faz parte do Grupo Playcenter o @playcenterfamilyoficial , localizado em São Paulo, no Shopping Aricanduva, oferece dezenas de atrações para todas as idades.

Welcome to #Flamingo Friday! 🦩 Did you know that flamingos feed with their bills upside-down? Did you know that April is Autism Awareness Month?

At LEGOLAND California, we have sensory guides available to all guests!  Rating each attractions’ sensory levels, the guides make it easier for families to plan activities that align with their needs and accommodations. Guests can also find a Park map marked with low-traffic areas for visitors in need of a low-sensory break area on the guides. Sensory guides are available at Guest Services.

Do you remember your first 'Big Kid' Roller Coaster?

Flash Back Friday! The original iteration of Santa's Village opened in May 1955, but eventually closed in 1998. Much of the park had been auctioned off when we reopened as SkyPark at Santa's Village in 2016. The new owners wanted to refurbish as much of the old park as possible. Now, thousands of guests who visited over the decades are able to retain the nostalgia for the original park!⁠
⁠
Do you have photos of yourself from the original Santa's Village? We'd love to see them and share great memories of years past. Tag us or send us a message to be featured in a future 'Then VS Now'!

Have you tried your hand at Princess Evergreen's Archery Range? Here are some tips to improve your archery skills:⁠
⁠
1. Proper posture: Stand up straight with your feet shoulder-width apart and your weight evenly distributed on both feet. Keep your shoulders relaxed and avoid leaning forward or backward.⁠
⁠
2. Hand placement: Grip the bow with a relaxed hand and place your fingers on the bowstring in the correct position for your type of bow. The string should rest on the first joint of your fingers, not in the crease.⁠
⁠
3. Aim small, miss small: Focus on a small target or a specific spot on the target. This will help you to be more precise in your aiming and improve your accuracy.⁠
⁠
4. Consistency: Develop a consistent routine for each shot, including your stance, draw, aim, and release. This will help you to develop muscle memory and improve your overall consistency.⁠
⁠
5. Practice regularly: Regular practice is essential for improving your archery skills. Set aside time each week to practice and track your progress over time.⁠
⁠
6. Seek out feedback: Ask for feedback from more experienced archers or our Outdoor Adventure crew to help you identify areas for improvement and develop a plan for addressing them.⁠
⁠
7. Stay focused: Stay focused on the present moment and avoid getting distracted by external factors. Maintain a positive attitude and focus on your goals to help you achieve success!⁠
⁠

Estamos participando de mais uma edição do DNA - Dia Nacional da Alegria! 

Essa iniciativa é organizada pelo SINDEPAT (@sindepat) - Sistema Integrado de Parques e Atrações Turísticas, em parceria com a ADIBRA (@adibraoficial) - Associação de Parques e Atrações do Brasil.

E durante o Dia Nacional da Alegria, vamos receber centenas de crianças em situação de vulnerabilidade social, assistida por diversas ONG's, que poderão desfrutar de momentos de alegria e diversão em nossas incríveis atrações. 

😍🎠🎢🧗‍♀️

Participam do DNA os Playlands: Grand Plaza, Center Norte, Eldorado, Interlagos e Osasco, além do Playcenter Family (@playcenterfamilyoficial) em São Paulo e Grande São Paulo, todos juntos para proporcionar uma experiência incrível!. 😊

Since zoo animals don't have the same changing environment as their wild counterparts, zookeepers regularly introduce different enrichment to appeal to animals' senses and stimulate their brains and bodies. 🧠 As you might guess, auditory enrichment refers to sounds added to the animal's environment. 🔈 Different sounds can prompt different reactions in animals, and might include anything from recordings of sounds from their natural habitat, sounds of other animals (the same or a different species) or even music chosen by the zookeepers. 🎵 Auditory enrichment is an important part of our comprehensive animal enrichment program, that contributes to animal welfare in zoos and helps to promote the physical and psychological health of the animals.

💐Check out some very exciting Easter Specials that can be found around the park this Saturday, April 8th! 🐰⁠
⁠
1. Peep-A-Licious Pineapple Whip! Pineapple soft-serve with sprinkles and marshmallow Peeps. Pick one up at Santa's Summer Shack across from the Bakery.⁠
⁠
2. The Cadbury Frappe! A vanilla caramel mocha + freshly cracked Cadbury Creme Egg. Available hot, blended, or with cold foam. Available at Kringle's Coffee and Gifts - Saturday only!⁠
⁠
3. Cookie Quest Treat! Find a Cookie Quest Coupon hidden throughout the park and redeem for a special Easter treat at the Gingerbread Sweet Shoppe. To allow everyone the opportunity to join the quest, please be kind and limit one per guest!⁠
⁠

Happy #MiloMonday! Milo and Cher are continuing to get familiar with each other. Despite being a social species, fennec foxes can be territorial and may take some time to warm up to a new companion. Milo is learning to respect Cher's space as he is a little more eager to play than she is. Cher is growing comfortable in her new home. 

#ICYMI Milo and Cher were transferred to Happy Hollow on the recommendation of the AZA Fennec Fox Species Survival plan. Fennec foxes are social animals so these two will be companions for each other here at Happy Hollow. They have completed a required quarantine period in Doc's Critter Care, and are now being introduced to each other before moving into the fennec fox habitat in the Zoo in the Hollow. Follow our social media for regular Milo and Cher updates! #MiloMonday

📸 Vet Tech Rachel and Keeper Heather

April is Autism Acceptance Month, and we are so proud to be a Certified Autism Center. All children deserve to have fun at the park, and we aim to provide that through specialized services for guests with autism and other special needs. ​

​We're also proud that the park provides children with an opportunity to meet Julia, a bright and curious four-year-old girl who has autism. Julia’s autism means that she does things a little differently than some people. Her good friend, Abby Cadabby, says she does things in “a Julia sort of way.” ​

column2: Six Flags Great Escape and Hurricane Harbor
column3:
50 days before we open!

Did you know we do the following to all our coasters before opening day?
🛠️Remove the coaster train (ride unit) from the ride structure
🛠️Take apart the ride unit down to the frames
🛠️Remove every nut, bolt, washer, bearing, race, and brushing
🛠️All framework goes through a nondestructive testing
🛠️Fiberglass and paint
🛠️Rebuild the unit from the ground up
🛠️Then we put it back on the ride structure

It takes approximately one full month per coaster to do all this before we start to test the ride for the season.

What’s all this “fascination” with the new game Roll-A-Bingo? Fascination, a game played like bingo, mesmerized visitors here at the Boardwalk from 1944-2008. A rubber handball was rolled down a wooden table, and as it dropped into a hole, a light lit up on the backboard. The first player to light up a row, won the round! Feeling nostalgic? Come play Roll-A-Bingo, a glowing modern version of the classic game! #TBT

Here's another #MiloMonday update! The fennec foxes are doing well and continuing to get to know one another. The zoo team has found that Milo is much more food motivated than Cher. Cher is more of a slow grazer, while Milo vacuums up any food he can find! This is an important observation that the team will need to plan for when Milo and Cher live together full-time, and will likely mean that the foxes will get their meals separately. 😜

#ICYMI Milo and Cher were transferred to Happy Hollow on the recommendation of the AZA Fennec Fox Species Survival plan. Fennec foxes are social animals so these two will be companions for each other here at Happy Hollow. They have completed a required quarantine period in Doc's Critter Care, and are now being introduced to each other before moving into the fennec fox habitat in the Zoo in the Hollow. Follow our social media for regular Milo and Cher updates! #MiloMonday

Among the notable events in our history are skywalks performed by members of the world-famous Wallenda family. The first skywalk took place in 1974 when 69-year-old Karl Wallenda broke a world skywalk distance record of 1,800 feet. His record stood for 34 years until 2008, when his grandson, Rick Wallenda, completed a 2,000-foot walk at the park. In 2009, Karl's great-grandson, Nik Wallenda, became the third member of the Wallenda family to perform at Kings Island with a skywalk that while not a record-breaker for distance, was performed at an incredible height of 262 feet in the air. Did you witness any of the Wallenda skywalks at the park? Let us know in the comments below. #TBT #KingsIsland

Are you seeing double? Surprise! Milo has a friend! Cher is a female fennec fox who will be Milo's companion. They are still in the introductory phase and getting comfortable with each other. Once introductions are well-established, the Zoo team will work out the logistics of moving them to the fennec fox habitat in the Zoo in the Hollow.

Milo and Cher were transferred to Happy Hollow on the recommendation of the AZA Fennec Fox Species Survival plan. Fennec foxes are social animals, so these two will be companions for each other here at Happy Hollow. They have completed a required quarantine period in Doc's Critter Care, and are now being introduced to each other before moving into the fennec fox habitat in the Zoo in the Hollow. Follow our social media for regular Milo and Cher updates! #MiloMonday

📸 Senior Keeper Alison and Zoo Curator Heather

Yesterday evening, SeaWorld Rescue was called to the scene of a pygmy sperm whale stranded at Carlsbad State Beach. With the help of the public, the animal was retrieved from the beach and SeaWorld’s rescue team administered emergency first aid, but unfortunately the whale passed away during transit. A necropsy will be performed at the Southwest Fisheries Science Center to determine what may have caused the animal to strand and its cause of death.

We’d like to thank the extraordinary efforts of everyone on scene that stayed with the animal, alerted authorities, and helped us move it up from the beach. While we all wish the outcome was different, our conservation community will do everything we can to learn more from this rarely seen whale species. 

Photo: Patrick Trolan / MediaBaller

https://fox5sandiego.com/news/local-news/beached-whale-found-in-carlsbad/

A glimpse of the past few days.

Believe it or not, this is only a fraction of the snow we had earlier this month! The rain this week has helped with some melt, making access to areas of the park more manageable. Currently SkyPark is still being utilized as a staging site for SoCal Gas as they complete necessary work around the mountain.

We're thrilled to see the local restaurants and businesses start to reopen again. Slowly but surely, the San Bernardino mountain communities are getting back to their normal routines, though there are still plenty of challenges. We're starting to get there as well, but just need a little more time. Stay tuned for another announcement later this week!

Marineland is deeply saddened by the recent passing of Kiska, the beloved orca who was a cherished member of the Marineland family. Our team has been privately grieving deeply over her loss, but will always remember the joy she brought to them and the visitors of Marineland. We take comfort in knowing that Kiska’s legacy will continue to live on through the lives she touched and memories she left behind. Our thoughts are with Kiska’s caregivers, past and present, and her many admirers, as they mourn this devastating loss.

#DYK that Happy Hollow is accepting book donations this month? And it's for a great cause! Our conservation partner, Kaminando Habitat Connectivity Initiative, works to protect jaguars 🐆 and their habitat in the cloud forests of Panama. To support their education initiative in local Panamanian schools, Happy Hollow will be collecting book donations until Monday, Apr. 3 📚 Children's picture books (about animals or nature) and Children's books in Spanish are particularly appreciated. New and used books are welcome ❤️ You can drop off donations in drop boxes in Happy Hollow's Guest Services or Administration buildings.

Disney Legend Rolly Crump, an Imagineer who was instrumental in the design of early Disneyland and Walt Disney World attractions, passed away Sunday at the age of 93. He brought his artistic talent to a multitude of Disney projects, including as an in-between artist and an assistant animator on films like Peter Pan, Lady and the Tramp, Sleeping Beauty. Most famously during his time at Walt Disney Imagineering, Crump served as a key designer for the 1964-1965 New York World's Fair attractions, as well as beloved classics like Haunted Mansion and Walt Disney's Enchanted Tiki Room.

After months of successful rehabilitation up in Alaska, it was time to determine what came next in Tyonek’s journey. Because of his age at stranding, coupled with the myriad of health issues he overcame in the first months of his life and his need for on-going human care, NOAA deemed Tyonek non-releasable. With an established, diverse pod with experienced mothers and young calves, SeaWorld San Antonio was chosen to provide his long-term care. Today, Tyonek is thriving, fully integrated with the pod, and even helping young beluga whale Tulok learn crucial skills and behaviors.

During our closure, SkyPark has been able to act as a command center for SoCal Gas, Edison and other utility and heavy machinery companies who have been rendering aid to our community. They have been working tirelessly around the clock to restore power, troubleshoot gas leaks and ensure the safety of mountain residents. The volume of snow we are navigating prevents sufficient space for these critical vehicles and equipment elsewhere. We are honored to do our part with providing a central place for them to meet and communicate as they plan out each day. We thank them for their dedication to maintaining power and accessibility to our mountain and getting people the help they need!

Last week, the SeaWorld San Diego Rescue Team returned a sea lion pup and a Northern elephant seal after successful rehabilitation at SeaWorld San Diego!​

The young male sea lion was rescued in January at La Jolla Cove. Upon examinations and x-rays, the veterinarian team discovered that the sea lion pup had ingested over 50-100 rocks that would need to be removed for him to recover. He was scoped by a team of trained veterinarians five times, and over a pound and a half of rocks were successfully removed from his stomach. Once healthy, he doubled in weight and was ready for return.​

The yearling Northern elephant seal was rescued from Imperial Beach with multiple cookie cutter shark bite wounds. She was brought to SeaWorld San Diego where her wounds were treated until they healed properly. Once she maintained a healthy weight and had fully healed, she was ready for return.​

This successful return would not have been possible without the care and expertise of the SeaWorld Rescue
So awesome! Can't wait!

On Sept. 30, 2017, Alaska SeaLife Center's Dr. Carrie Goertz was in the field necropsying an adult beluga whale when she received a call from NOAA about another carcass. Turns out: it wasn’t a carcass at all; it was Tyonek the baby Cook Inlet beluga whale, stranded on a mudflat and clinging to life. Dr. Goertz was rushed to the site to assess his state, and it determined he was a candidate for rescue, as he was in good body condition, despite signs of trauma and scavenger damage. Since his pod was nowhere in sight, the team transported him back to ASLC’s facility to begin the rehabilitation process.

Happy #MiloMonday! #DYK: cats aren't the only animal that will use a litterbox or exhibit a latrine behavior 😮 When Milo first arrived at Happy Hollow, zookeepers made sure there was a container of dirt in his quarantine space to encourage digging behavior. He went beyond just digging, and essentially latrine-trained himself! He has been using it like a litter box ever since. Just a reminder that this doesn’t mean fennec foxes make good pets. The litter box doesn’t stop Milo from scent-marking his territory, and the zookeepers say the quarantine area smells like a skunk is living in there! 🤢

ICYMI, Milo was recently transferred to Happy Hollow on the recommendation of the AZA Fennec Fox Species Survival plan and is currently completing a required quarantine period in Doc's Critter Care. Once he has cleared his quarantine and passed a final veterinary exam, he will move to his new home, the fennec fox habitat in the Zoo in the Hollow. Follow our social media for regular Milo updates!

Last week, our rescue team was called to assist with the rescue of a 2 year old dolphin calf in Sarasota. The calf was spotted swimming alongside her mother, but struggling to use her tail fluke due to an entanglement in fishing gear. Partners from Brookfield Zoo, MyFWC Florida Fish and Wildlife, Clearwater Marine Aquarium, Mote Marine Laboratory & Aquarium, FAU Harbor Branch Oceanographic Institute, Sarasota Police Department, and University of Florida College of Veterinary Medicine were able to successfully remove the gear and return both animals onsite.

Throwback to THEN vs NOW! (Of course, there's a LOT more snow now!)

The Old Fire of 2003 was one of the worst wildfires in state history, ravaging much of the Santa's Village property and its neighbors. If not for the extraordinary staging efforts of local fire agencies, the Village would have been destroyed. The fire was exacerbated by a previous bark beetle infestation that weakened the already drought-stricken trees. Years later, the Santa’s Village property was chosen to store and process millions of infested logs, as seen here in the first photo.

Restoring the historic qualities of the park was paramount in our efforts to reopen in December of 2016. Today, SkyPark at Santa's Village continues to transform into a nostalgic, dazzling Christmas wonderland every winter. Throughout the rest of the year, we also offer mountain biking, active outdoor activities, fishing, hiking, ziplining and comprehensive education programs.

You’ve probably come across some of the stunningly dramatic photos of when it snowed here in 1976. Did you know there was also snow on the beach in 1957? Check out these cool photos—notice the old Fun House on the left in the first image. 🏖❄️🤡🎢 #TBT

PARK UPDATE!

What a WILD past week! The historic blizzard that hit the Southern California mountains is finally starting to diminish. But the effects are not quite over yet. Highways leading up to the mountain remain closed to non-residents. Like thousands of others, most of us are still in a holding pattern at home while we patiently await our roads to be plowed. Some areas received over 6 feet of snow and our mountains made national news. This was no ordinary snow storm. Some of us have never experienced this in our lifetime and are still processing the past few days. 

Due to the severity of the storm, SkyPark will remain CLOSED through the week and until further notice. We will have an intense amount of snow removal and storm repair that cannot be rushed. Many steps need to be taken in order to ensure it's safe to welcome guests back to the Park. 

Thank you for all your messages and concerns over the past week. We've definitely felt the love and cannot wait to see everyone again soon. We will update more as highways reopen to visitors and progress is made, so be sure to follow us for more!

This first-of-its-kind single-rail family coaster races two dueling trains on a cumulative 1,124 feet of weld free track! Riders will be immersed in their very own comic book story with an innovative LED lighting display, transforming the top and sides of the tracks into a kaleidoscope of colors. 

KID FLASH Cosmic Coaster will be Georgia's first single-rail coaster and Georgia's only racing coaster.

For our final feature during #BlackHistoryMonth, we'd like to acknowledge Dr. Mamie Parker for her achievements as the first African American Fish and Wildlife Service Regional Director. She also served as the US Fish and Wildlife Service's Chief of Staff, and Assistant Director of Habitat Conservation/ Head of Fisheries. One of the many highlights of Dr. Parker’s work with fish habitat management was her role in negotiating with General Electric to clean up the Hudson River.

This year, the SeaWorld Conservation Fund is celebrating 20 years of grants supporting third party research, rescue, and conservation programs geared towards protecting marine animals and their habitats. Recipients like Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution (WHOI) and Texas Marine Mammal Stranding Network are doing impactful work to help many different species, including the critically endangered North Atlantic right whales, killer whales, bottlenose dolphins, manatees, penguins, coral reefs, and many more. Click the link to learn more about the 22 grants made in 2022: https://bit.ly/41t9LuJ

Happy #MiloMonday! Is Milo hiding or sleeping in these pictures? Maybe both! Fennec Foxes have a sandy-colored coat which helps them camouflage in their natural desert habitat. Fennec Foxes will sleep in their burrows during the day to both hide from the heat and from predators. 

ICYMI, Milo was recently transferred to Happy Hollow on the recommendation of the AZA Fennec Fox Species Survival plan and is currently completing a required quarantine period in Doc's Critter Care. Once he has cleared his quarantine and passed a final veterinary exam, he will move to his new home, the fennec fox habitat in the Zoo in the Hollow. Follow our social media for regular Milo updates!

The Southern California mountain ranges have been issued our first BLIZZARD warning since 1989! We are in the middle of an extremely rare event, friends! 🥶❄️

Though this is quite unusual for us, Arrow is pretty excited about it (for now). While we all continue to stay safe and warm inside during our snow closure, this is a reminder to please exercise caution if you must travel on the roads during this time. Travel will be extremely difficult to impossible in the mountains. Please regularly check the Caltrans QuickMap for highway conditions and chain control (currently at R3 meaning ALL vehicles must have chains/traction control on their tires regardless of AWD or 4x4).

Caltrans QuickMap: https://quickmap.dot.ca.gov/

Pollinators carry pollen from plant to plant, helping plants produce fruit, seeds and new plants. To encourage pollinators like hummingbirds and butterflies in your garden, you can take actions like planting native flowers, limiting pesticide use and providing water or shelter for pollinators.

Happy Hollow Park & Zoo and Happy Hollow Foundation’s Progress for Pollinators grant program seeks community members who are dedicated to creating pollinator-friendly habitats. The spring application deadline is March 1- learn more and apply at www.happyhollow.org/progress-for-pollinators

Fennec foxes are opportunistic omnivores, which means they eat whatever they can find, be it small mammals, insects or plants. In the wild, fennec foxes hunt or forage for their food. Here at Happy Hollow, the zoo team uses puzzle feeders and other enrichment strategies to bring out Milo's natural foraging behaviors. Milo has proven his skills as a master forager and can find foods in all types of puzzle feeders and enrichment toys.

ICYMI, Milo was recently transferred to Happy Hollow on the recommendation of the AZA Fennec Fox Species Survival plan and is currently completing a required quarantine period in Doc's Critter Care. Once he has cleared his quarantine and passed a final veterinary exam, he will move to his new home, the fennec fox habitat in the Zoo in the Hollow. Follow our social media for regular Milo updates!

Six Flags Fun Fact: Did you know a former president has ridden one of our rides? 

Riverview Carousel, originally built by the Philadelphia Toboggan Company in 1908 for Riverview Park in Chicago, Illinois, was ridden by the 29th president of the United States, Warren G. Harding, over 100 years ago! Six Flags Over Georgia purchased and restored the historic carousel in 1971, after the closure of Riverview Park. 

Today the attraction can be found on top of Carousel Hill along with Up, Up and Away, Hanson Cars, and Rockin' Tug. Riverview Carousel was placed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1995 and celebrated its 50th anniversary at our park just last year. 🎠 

#PresidentsDay #RiverviewPark #SixFlagsOverGeorgia #SixFlags

**2/22/23 PARK CLOSURE UPDATE: Due to the extended forecast of over 4 feet of total snow accumulation, SkyPark will remain temporarily closed for storm clean up and repairs through March 3rd. We are scheduled to reopen on March 4th, 2023!**

Have you heard? Over 3 feet of snow is forecasted to head our way beginning this Wednesday! 😮❄️

A true Winter Wonderland will be dropping throughout the San Bernardino Mountains. As we prepare for the storm, we are also keeping the safety and comfort of our guests in mind. The total accumulation predicted will create hazardous road and park conditions, so SkyPark will be temporarily closed this Thursday, February 23rd and Friday, February 24th. During this time, our staff will be continuously plowing and clearing snow throughout each day with the goal of reopening as soon as possible. 

We will continue to track how the storm progresses to provide a confirmation on weekend operations as the days go on. The @skyparkbikepark bike trails will be temporarily unavailable for riding until further notice for storm clean up and repairs.

If it's not essential to be on the mountain roads during the upcoming storm, please stay safe at home. And always check the Caltrans QuickMap for current road conditions and for chain control. Chains will definitely be required.

Any guesses on how much snow we'll actually receive? Drop a '❄️' in the comments below if you think it'll be only 1 foot of snow, drop a '🧊' if you think 2 feet, drop a '☃️' if you think 3 feet and drop a '🥶' if you think 4 feet or more!
We saved you a seat 😵

Throughout #BlackHistoryMonth, Happy Hollow is featuring members of the Black community who have had an important impact on zoology and/or conservation. This week we're spotlighting Charles Henry Turner, who was likely the first black entomologist in North America.

Turner was a trailblazer in the study of insect behavior and differed from other entomologists of his time. He studied insects' learning, memory and expectations when others believed insects only reacted to external stimuli. Notably, Turner discovered that honeybees can see visual patterns and color 🐝

Meadowlands has quite the history!

From the earliest inhabitants following the migratory trails of wildlife, to early settlers logging the forest, to digging a pond and planting an orchard as they established homes and businesses, from pasturing domestic animals like horses, cows, and sheep, to becoming a designated storage site for thousands of drought-weakened, bark beetle-infested trees, from hosting a rave that attracted more than 10,000 partygoers, to the smooth sounds of the Bue Jay Jazz Festival concert series, from enduring and surviving one of the worst wildfires in California history, and to the present day restoration efforts, Meadowlands has been through it all.

Have you taken a walk, bike or train ride through Meadowlands?

Pollinators carry pollen from plant to plant, helping the plant to produce fruit, seeds and new plants. When you think of pollinators, you probably think of insects like bees and butterflies first, but birds flying between plants can also help spread pollen! Keep a look out for these avian pollinators you might see right in your own backyard.

In honor of the upcoming Presidents' Day holiday, today's #ThrowbackThursday is of President Teddy Roosevelt’s visit to Santa Cruz in 1903. There’s no coincidence that Santa Cruz promoter extraordinaire Fred Swanton ramped up his efforts that same year. Fred was a member of the President’s welcome group that hosted him for a barbecue in the redwoods. These efforts were not in vain, as Roosevelt went on to describe his visit as, “Dee-lightful!” Fred’s promotional fervor only grew after the president’s visit, as the first Neptune Casino was built the following year (the origin of the Boardwalk we know today). 🏖🎠🌴 #TBT

We are proud to announce the addition of two Top Golf Swing Suites, bowling lanes, and The Lagoon Bar!  
 
Waterville USA will house the most advanced golf and interactive multiport simulator, Top Golf Swing Suites, available, for fun and interactive social gatherings or private practice sessions. This will be in addition to extensive lineup of attractions including a waterpark, two Escape Rooms, the Flowrider, updated go-carts, 36 holes of miniature golf, Fun Depot kiddie rides, and an arcade.
The Topgolf Swing Suites will feature two simulator bays and a variety of virtual games. Play the world’s greatest golf courses or enjoy Quarterback Challenge, Zombie Dodgeball, Baseball Pitching, Soccer, Hockey Shots, and more – paired with comfortable lounge seating, and food and beverage service including alcoholic beverages. The Top Golf Swing Suites can accommodate up to eight people in each bay, where they can play, eat, drink and hang out. The spaces will also be available to rent for business and social gatherings, including birthday and bachelorette/bachelor parties, team building events, corporate meetings and more.

We are also adding two 36-foot interactive bowling lanes. Rather than name the lanes, customers are invited to compete in a Facebook competition to submit their name suggestions. We will select a name and the winner will receive a FREE season pass to the waterpark, along with free bowling passes! Participants can enter to win at http://watervilleuse.com/contest. 

The Lagoon Bar will also be a new addition in 2023. Relax and enjoy an alcoholic beverage or refreshing frozen drink white watching the HD TVs at the new bar located just outside the amusement park on the newly renovated deck.  An expanded food menu in the amusement park will be offered as well.  

We will keep you updated on Social Media as well as on our website at watervilleusa.com!

We are excited to announce a new program we developed at Silverwood called Fostering Family Fun. Starting in May 2023, Silverwood will offer foster children in the state of Idaho the opportunity to visit Silverwood for FREE once a year through our new Fostering Family Fun program! Family members will also qualify for discounted tickets when showing a valid Idaho ID at the gate. This program is designed to help foster families make new memories and have fun together.

In 2023, we are only offering this program to the state of Idaho, but we are looking at ways to expand to our neighboring states in the coming years.

If you know anyone that could benefit from this program, they can find more information at https://sw4.fun/Foster

TOP 5: Atrações para as crianças! 🎠

Alô alô Papais e Mamães! Esse post é dedicado para vocês 🤓

Hoje eu separei aqui as minhas 5 atrações que fazem maior sucesso entre as crianças - elas amam! 

5. Jogos: de habilidade, competição e até de sorte, além de muitos simuladores que brilham os olhos das crianças - a maioria dos jogos liberam tickets conforme a pontuação, que podem ser trocados por prêmios no Ticketmania! 🕹🧸
(os jogos estão em todos os Playlands!)

4. Carrossel: é tradicional e clássico de todo parque de diversões, todo mundo se encanta com as luzes e a magia do Carrossel. 🎠
(o Carrossel está presente em todos os Playlands!)

3. Kid Pirata/Kid Play: um percurso com obstáculos, escorregadores e a famosa piscina de bolinhas.🔵
(essa atração está presente em todos os Playlands, nas versões Kid Pirata, Kid Play ou Super Kid Play)

2. Rally: uma atração giratória onde as crianças embarcam em carrinhos coloridos que simulam um rally, espalhando lama (de brincadeira) para todos os lados. 🚗
(essa atração está disponível no Playland Interlagos) 

1. Magic Bikes: que tal embarcar em bicicletas voadoras? Essa é a proposta dessa atração que é única no Brasil. 🚲
(essa atração está disponível no Playland Eldorado) 

- Viu só quanta coisa legal tem para fazer aqui? Tudo isso em ambiente coberto, com ar-condicionado e muita segurança. 🤓

- Ah, importante! Para brincar nas atrações é necessário obedecer algumas normas e restrições de segurança, além de possuir a altura mínima para acesso - consulte todas essas informações nas placas que estão na entrada das atrações, ou na página 'atrações' no meu site (o link está no meu perfil). Vem que eu tô te esperando! ❤
.
.
.

It's #MiloMonday! Did you know that fennec foxes are mostly nocturnal animals? In their natural habitat, they avoid the hottest part of the desert day by hiding out in their underground burrows. Here is Milo resting up despite the light of day is streaming into his enclosure, giving into his natural urge for midday naps.  

ICYMI, Milo was recently transferred to Happy Hollow on the recommendation of the AZA Fennec Fox Species Survival plan and is currently completing a required quarantine period in Doc's Critter Care. Once he has cleared his quarantine and passed a final veterinary exam, he will move to his new home, the fennec fox habitat in the Zoo in the Hollow. Follow our social media for regular Milo updates!

Got Valentine's date night on your mind? Did you know that zoo animals can have dates, too? As an AZA-accredited zoo, Happy Hollow participates in Species Survival Plan (SSP) programs when it comes to setting up animal 'dates.' 

Under an SSP, experts will recommend two individuals of a species for breeding based on genetics and demographics to ensure that the species remains as healthy and genetically diverse as possible. 

It's much less romantic than a human's valentine's day date, but it helps keep animal populations healthy and stable, and it can result in some very cute baby animals.

It's National Pizza Day and St. Nick's Patio & Grille has just what you need to celebrate the occasion! Indulge with our most popular pizzas: the 'Freckled Elf' with our homemade pizza sauce, mozzarella, fresh tomatoes and pepperoni or the 'Rooftop' with BBQ chicken, BBQ sauce, mozzarella, red onion and cilantro. Gluten-free dough is also available upon request.

Here's some fun facts about 🍕 you might not have known:

-Americans eat 350 slices of pizza every SECOND!
-The most popular topping is pepperoni 
-The first pizzeria in the US opened in 1905 in New York City.
-Super Bowl Sunday is the biggest pizza delivery day of the entire year. Meanwhile, Thanksgiving Day is the least popular day for pizza.
-Almost 20% of restaurants in the US are pizza restaurants
-61% of Americans prefer thin crust pizza. Do you?
-There is an annual pizza expo in Las Vegas

Now go out there and enjoy some pie! 😋

Puppets at Santa's Village have been around for a long time. Originally known as the Wee Puppet Theater, guests could watch shows in the building that is now Christmas Coachworks. Today, our puppet show themes rotate seasonally and can be seen in the Sky Pavilion. Christmas Coachworks offers various concessions throughout the year like soups during winter and dole whip during the summer. It's a great place to take photos with our NorthWoods characters. A pumpkin patch can also be found here during our annual fall festival, Pumpkins in the Pines, and sometimes an opportunity to see Santa when he's not in his house!

Pollinators carry pollen from plant to plant, helping plants produce fruit, seeds and new plants. Bees and butterflies are often the first pollinators that jump to mind, but many other insects, including different types of beetles, wasps, moths and flies, also carry pollen between plants.

Happy Hollow Park & Zoo and Happy Hollow Foundation’s Progress for Pollinators grant program seeks community members who are dedicated to creating pollinator-friendly habitats. Apply today for a mini-grant of up to $2,500 to make your pollinator dreams come true! Visit Happy Hollow's website and look for the link on the home page.

Throughout Black History Month, Happy Hollow will be highlighting the achievements of members of the Black community who have influenced zoology and conservation as it exists today. First up is Roger Arliner Young, the first African American woman to earn a Ph.D. in zoology. 

Her achievements, including her published research in Science magazine, paved the way for other Black women and women of color to pursue zoology professionally.

The Roger Arliner Young (RAY) Marine Conservation Diversity Fellowship was created in Young’s honor, to support emerging leaders of color who want to become involved in marine environmental conservation work.

Pollinators carry pollen from plant to plant, helping the plant to produce fruit, seeds and new plants. Bees make excellent pollinators because most of their life is spent collecting pollen, which they use as a source of protein to feed to their developing young. 🌻 🐝 

Happy Hollow Park & Zoo and Happy Hollow Foundation’s Progress for Pollinators grant program seeks community members who are dedicated to creating pollinator-friendly habitats. Apply today for mini-grants of up to $2,500 to create your own pollinator paradise! Qualifying projects must be located within Santa Clara County, be accessible to the public and have a teaching component. Schools, Scout groups, community groups and non-profit organizations are encouraged to apply. Learn more and submit your application on our website through the Explore tab, then 'Conservation.'

SeaWorld has been at the forefront of marine animal research ever since the opening of the Hubbs-SeaWorld Research Institute back in 1963. In 2022 alone, our scientists have published 18 new studies that are critical to conservation efforts, as what we are able to learn from the animals in our care helps conserve wild populations of these species, some of which are vulnerable and endangered. On a recent episode of our Sea the World podcast, we sat down with VP of Conservation Research Dr. Robeck to learn more about the important work and what it means for the future of marine species across the globe. https://apple.co/3RCRCpK

Don’t go breaking out the Hawaiian shirts, sunscreen and flip flops quite yet. The Beast spotted its shadow at Kings Island this morning, forecasting six more weeks of winter. 

If you’re unfamiliar with the tradition, if The Beast sees its shadow it means six more weeks of winter. If The Beast can’t see its shadow, it means it predicts an early spring. 

Every Feb. 2, roller coaster aficionados in southwest Ohio wait anxiously for The Beast to let us know what to anticipate.

Over the 16 years of recorded history, it is the sixth time the world's longest wooden roller coaster has seen its shadow and for the second time in three years.

Year-by-Year Beast Day predictions:
• 2023 – Longer Winter
• 2022 – Early Spring
• 2021 – Longer Winter
• 2020 – Early Spring
• 2019 – Early Spring
• 2018 – Early Spring
• 2017 – Early Spring
• 2016 – Early Spring
• 2015 – Longer Winter
• 2014 – Longer Winter
• 2013 – Early Spring
• 2012 – Longer Winter
• 2011 – Early Spring
• 2010 – Early Spring
• 2009 – Longer Winter
• 2008 – Early Spring

Position Description: Responsible for Lookout Grille Kitchen & Smokehouse Kitchen and other food service operations.                      
 
Responsibilities:
-Lead and guide all F&B back of house employees with a positive attitude.
-Work a front line position in any location as needed.
-Work with Kitchen supervisor to determine staffing needs and ensure adequate employee coverage while working within labor budget. 
-Constantly look at individual performance to ensure each employee works to the maximum potential. Giving positive reinforcement & performing audits. 
-Conducting performance appraisals at the end of the season. 
-Ensure all customers receive an excellent meal in a timely fashion.
-Maintain food safety guidelines and monitor time & temp logs.
-Have the ability to proactively asses the priorities of all the restaurant operations.
-Work with all F & B Leads & Supervisors to ensure lead coverage in all locations.
-Ensure kitchen is clean and safe. Make sure daily & weekly cleaning is being done.
-Help to train new employees using provided training materials & checklists.
-Work closely with F&B leadership to suggest and finalize menu items, ordering procedures and special event criteria.
-Be ready, willing and able to assist with food truck deliveries.
-Assist with special events, banquets, company parties, birthday parties and weddings when needed.
-Complete other tasks or duties as they are assigned by your supervisor.

Ever stay up late wondering how coral stays healthy? The Ricordea florida mushroom coral at SeaWorld San Antonio gets most of its nutrients from photosynthesis, which is why UV lamps are in place to keep it thriving. This type of coral also feeds off nutrients in the water, so the care team makes sure the water is just right.

Enrichment for Happy Hollow's animals comes in many different forms. Visual enrichment refers to new and interesting things for an animal to look at, which can include moving around objects or 'furniture' in an animal's habitat to give them a new view, or adding new natural or man-made items to, or within view of, the habitat. For animals with good color vision, like Kengele the African spurred tortoise, Happy Hollow zookeepers sometimes add unique artwork to their space as enrichment!

OCÊ JÁ CONHECE O PLAYMANIA?

✨O Playmania é o e-commerce do Grupo Playcenter. Lá você encontra ofertas e promoções incríveis para se divertir aqui no Playland e também no Playcenter Family.

🎠 Aproveite combos especiais que incluem créditos para brincar, bônus e até mesmo tickets. No Playmania você encontra várias opções de ofertas, uma melhor que a outra.

🎫 Já tem um Playcard? Dentro do Playmania você consegue associar o seu cartão ao seu nome, dessa maneira você nunca perde seus créditos, bônus ou tickets acumulados, pois fica tudo em seu nome.

- Não perca essa dica e acesse o Playmania agora mesmo, o link está em nosso perfil! Ou você pode acessa-lo através do endereço: playmania.com.br

Restoring the historic buildings at Santa's Village is something we're extremely proud of. One of our most popular buildings, the Pedal Pub, was something quite different many years ago. Does anyone remember what the Pedal Pub used to be?

Today, the Pub is a favorite break spot for our 21+ crowd. Warm up during Winter Wonderland with one of our seasonal hot drinks like an Irish Coffee or Taste of Winter. The food menu from St. Nick's Patio & Grille is also available to order inside the pub, so it's your perfect mid-day stop!

Ready for your next #NewAnimal Hint❔ This meal is going to make our newest residents very happy. 

These animals are very social and they live in family groups. They are close relatives to squirrels, and they get their names from 2 aspects of their lives. The first part of their name comes from their habitat, and the second comes from their warning calls which sound like barks. 🧐

MOTIVOS PARA VOCÊ VIR BRINCAR:

🚗🚇🚌 - Acesso: estou localizado nos principais shoppings em São Paulo e na Bahia, no meu site (link no perfil) você encontra o endereço de todas as minhas unidades. Algumas ficam do lado de estações do metrô ou trem e todas tem fácil acesso! 

☀🌧 - Faça chuva ou faça sol: meus Parques são totalmente cobertos e com ar-condicionado, você aproveita mesmo se o clima lá fora estiver ruim.

🤑 - Passeio democrático: a entrada no Playland é grátis! E você só paga pelas atrações que quiser utilizar. No meu Caixa ou no Playmania você encontra diversos combos promocionais para aproveitar ainda mais.

🎠 - Atrações: todo mundo se diverte aqui, tem atrações para todos os gostos! E a maioria permite que pais e filhos brinquem juntos.

🕹 - Jogos: além das atrações, também ofereço dezenas de jogos de habilidade e competição, a galera se diverte de montão!

🎟 - Tickets: você sabia que a maioria dos jogos liberam tickets? É isso mesmo! Conforme a sua pontuação você acumula tickets que podem ser trocados por prêmios. É brincar, juntar e trocar!

🎈 - Festas: aqui é o lugar ideal para comemorar o seu aniversário. Tenho vários salões de festas exclusivos que podem ser locados para a sua comemoração ser ainda mais divertida. (para mais informações acesse o site com o link do meu perfil e clique em 'faça sua festa').

- Olha quantos motivos para você vir brincar! Tô te esperando hein!?

Happy #MiloMonday! Here's a cute video of Milo playing with some of his enrichment 😍 Even though fennec foxes are objectively adorable, they are wild animals and do not make good pets. 

They are territorial animals and will use their (very smelly) urine or feces to mark their territory in your home. Fennec foxes naturally live in underground dens, which means they have a habit of burrowing that would likely lead to ruined carpet and flooring. Fennec foxes are nocturnal animals that are high energy when awake, yet skittish and shy. They typically do not enjoy being handled, much less cuddled, so they are very different from a small dog, despite the familial relationship.

ICYMI, Milo was recently transferred to Happy Hollow on the recommendation of the AZA Fennec Fox Species Survival plan and is currently completing a required quarantine period in Doc's Critter Care. Once he has cleared his quarantine and passed a final veterinary exam, he will move to his new home, the fennec fox habitat in the Zoo in the Hollow. Follow our social media for regular Milo updates!

New Animal Reveal! Introducing Tiffany the Tamandua! 

Tamanduas are a small type of anteaters. They are arboreal, which means they spend most of their time in trees. Their prehensile tails can grasp onto branches, helping them maintain balance as they climb high above the ground. Tamanduas have sticky tongues that are nearly 16 inches long, and are perfect bug catchers! 🐜 

You can meet Tiffany and her sister Tasha during animal meet & greets or in their new home at Oasis Outpost.

Our Rescue team recently received a Guadalupe fur seal pup from our partners Channel Islands Marine & Wildlife Institute (CIMWI). The young male was rescued after he was found stranded on a road, displaced after a storm. CIMWI provided the pup with immediate medical care and have moved him to SeaWorld San Diego, where we'll be caring for him long-term as he begins journey to recovery. The rescue team and veterinarians are providing around-the-clock care and monitoring the pup to ensure his health continues to improve.​

Guadalupe fur seals are recovering from near extinction and are listed as threatened under the Endangered Species Act and depleted under the Marine Mammal Protection Act. As a Marine Mammal Health & Stranding Response Program partner, SeaWorld has the expertise and NOAA Fisheries Service authorization for Guadalupe fur seal rehabilitation.

Fennec Fox Milo continues to do well during his quarantine period in Doc's Critter Care 🦊💛 Each meal, his care team utilizes different forms of enrichment, such as this puzzle feeder, to encourage natural behaviors and ensure Milo's foraging skills are in tip-top shape. Fennex foxes are omnivores, eating a variety of meat and plants. Milo's favorite food is one that he wouldn't likely find in a fennec fox's natural desert habitat- broccoli! 🥦  #MiloMonday

ICYMI, Milo was recently transferred to Happy Hollow on the recommendation of the AZA Fennec Fox Species Survival plan and is currently completing a required quarantine period in Doc's Critter Care. Once he has cleared his quarantine and passed a final veterinary exam, he will move to his new home, the fennec fox habitat in the Zoo in the Hollow. Follow our social media for regular Milo updates!

📹: Vet Tech Rachel

Activities conducted under the Stranding Agreement between NMFS and SeaWorld Florida under the Authority of the MMPA.

Thank you to everyone who has inquired about the stranded and deceased killer whale in Palm Coast on January 11. What we know so far about her is that she was an older adult female killer whale almost 22 feet in length and weighing in at 9,000 pounds. It will be several weeks or months before her necropsy report is finalized; however, we can confirm that, contrary to what some of the public has speculated, there are no signs that she was pregnant. There were no signs of human interaction or trauma. There were signs of various illnesses. The whale was extensively sampled during necropsy (animal autopsy) to determine causes of illness and death, and those samples will be sent to labs around the country for analysis in the coming days to weeks.   

In the meantime, we want to thank all our partners, including Hubbs-SeaWorld Research Institute, MyFWC Florida Fish and Wildlife, University of Florida, Blue World Research Institute and National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) for their hard work and dedication. We also want to acknowledge and thank  Volusia County Environmental Management, FWC Law Enforcement, Palm Coast Fire Department, Flagler County Sheriff's Office, and other local groups that were on the scene to help. And we want to extend heartfelt gratitude to the individual who first spotted her stranded and called for help. Remember, if you spot a marine animal in trouble, contact the 24-hour hotline: 1-877-WHALE HELP (1-877-942-5343).

For more details, click here: https://bit.ly/3H3HjXV

We're 'wheeling' it back to the 70s for #ThrowbackThursday! 🎡 The Wheelie was a Schwarzkopf Enterprise ride that spun passengers round and round as it rose from a horizontal position to a vertical one.

The Wheelie opened in 1977 and could originally be found in the USA section of the park. In 1985 it was moved to Lickskillet, where it stayed until its removal in 2012, making way for SkyScreamer.

Generations of kids loved the Fun House (1925-1971) with its giant wooden slide, undulating 50-foot walkway, rotating barrel, and fast-spinning disk. The old-fashioned fun house kept kids entertained for hours. In fact, at one point, it was nicknamed 'babysitting headquarters' because kids could stay and play all day for fifty cents! Do you have a favorite Fun House memory? 🤡🛝🪞#TBT

winter wonderland ❄️

The snow has left Lake Compounce looking like a winter wonderland!

Ever wondered what we do with our Christmas trees after Christmas Town? Well, here is your answer. 🌲

Fun Fact: Apart from serving as enrichment for Poppy & Thistle, the majority of our live trees are ground up and sprinkled into mulch throughout the park by our landscaping team!

Throwback to THEN vs NOW!

The castle that now sits in the center of Arrow's Adventure, formerly known as the Silver Slipper Castle, used to look a little different. When the original Santa's Village opened in the 1950s, the park was designed with a fairytale/storybook look in mind. The castle was open on both sides for children to play and run across the drawbridge. 

And do you recognize the colorful tables and stools by the castle? You can still find some around the park on the way to the Village Tree!
